<BaseLayout title="Case Study — Public Transport ETA">
  <article class="prose max-w-none">
    <h1>Real‑time Bus ETA — Headways & Data Fusion</h1>
    <p><strong>Role:</strong> Data / PM</p>
    <h2>Context</h2>
    <p>City bus system; uneven headways and unreliable arrival predictions.</p>
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>High variance in ETAs during peak hours led to user frustration and operational inefficiency.</p>
    <h2>Process</h2>
    <p>Ingested GPS, schedule, and incident feeds; compared Kalman vs. gradient models; designed SLA for latency.</p>
    <h2>Execution</h2>
    <p>Implemented headway normalization and anomaly alerts; improved ETA pipeline with caching.</p>
    <h2>Results</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>−18% mean absolute ETA error</li>
      <li>+12% on-time arrivals</li>
      <li>Sub‑500ms P95 latency</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Lessons</h2>
    <p>Prioritize data freshness; expose uncertainty; align ops with model feedback.</p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
